1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,405
Thus far in the lesson,

2

00:00:01,405  -->  00:00:04,955
we've only looked at relationships between quantitative variables.

3

00:00:04,955  -->  00:00:07,700
We'll now look at the relationship between our fuel efficiency

4

00:00:07,700  -->  00:00:11,435
variable against the qualitative variable, Vehicle class.

5

00:00:11,435  -->  00:00:15,970
Note here that I've used Pandas as type function to convert the V class column from

6

00:00:15,970  -->  00:00:17,560
a plain object type into

7

00:00:17,559  -->  00:00:21,219
an ordered categorical type putting the classes in order of size.

8

00:00:21,219  -->  00:00:24,239
This way, the sorting of levels is automatic and I

9

00:00:24,239  -->  00:00:27,699
won't need a second order parameter in my visualization calls.

10

00:00:27,699  -->  00:00:31,239
The prototype I'll be going over in this video is the violin plot.

11

00:00:31,239  -->  00:00:33,539
When we use seaborn's violin plot function in

12

00:00:33,539  -->  00:00:36,979
the usual way setting the data x and y variables,

13

00:00:36,979  -->  00:00:39,229
we get the following plot.

14

00:00:39,429  -->  00:00:42,505
We should clean this up a little bit first.

15

00:00:42,505  -->  00:00:46,130
I'm going to use the color palette function to make sure each level is

16

00:00:46,130  -->  00:00:50,425
the same color and the Xticks function to slightly rotate the labels.

17

00:00:50,424  -->  00:00:52,359
For now, I'm also going to set

18

00:00:52,359  -->  00:00:55,890
the inner equals none parameter to clean up the middle of the plots.

19

00:00:55,890  -->  00:00:58,445
I'll get back to this parameter later on.

20

00:00:58,445  -->  00:01:00,554
For each of the vehicle classes,

21

00:01:00,554  -->  00:01:03,229
an area is plotted that shows the approximate density

22

00:01:03,229  -->  00:01:06,265
of efficiency values for each vehicle class.

23

00:01:06,265  -->  00:01:08,954
They're like density curves turned on their sides.

24

00:01:08,954  -->  00:01:11,159
From this plot, we can see that there isn't

25

00:01:11,159  -->  00:01:14,744
a monotonic relationship between car size and fuel efficiency.

26

00:01:14,745  -->  00:01:17,740
The largest cars seem to have the lowest fuel efficiencies,

27

00:01:17,739  -->  00:01:21,583
but the longtail suggest outliers with the highest of efficiencies.

28

00:01:21,584  -->  00:01:24,109
Mini compact and subcompact cars have

29

00:01:24,109  -->  00:01:25,909
the next best efficiencies but

30

00:01:25,909  -->  00:01:29,094
the distribution for mini compact cars is much more peaked.

31

00:01:29,094  -->  00:01:31,590
Finally, compact and midsize cars have

32

00:01:31,590  -->  00:01:33,920
the best efficiencies but the distribution of

33

00:01:33,920  -->  00:01:36,995
the midsize cars is broader than the compacts.

34

00:01:36,995  -->  00:01:41,390
Let's briefly go back to the plot without the inner equals non parameter setting.

35

00:01:41,390  -->  00:01:45,745
The thing that is plotted in each violin is a miniature box plot.

36

00:01:45,745  -->  00:01:48,740
A box plot is another quantitative versus qualitative

37

00:01:48,739  -->  00:01:51,799
plot type that takes a summary approach to displaying the data.

38

00:01:51,799  -->  00:01:55,399
I'll give more details about box plots in the next video.
